  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What do you do when you have no friends?",
  "response": "I'm really sorry you're feeling this way. Here are some steps you might consider to help build connections and improve how you're feeling:\n\n1. **Reach Out to Existing Contacts**: Sometimes reconnecting with family members, classmates, or coworkers you haven't spoken to in a while can help rekindle relationships.\n\n2. **Engage in Activities You Enjoy**: Pursuing hobbies or interests can provide opportunities to meet others with similar passions. Whether it's joining a sports team, taking a class, or participating in a creative workshop, shared activities can foster connections.\n\n3. **Join Clubs or Groups**: Look for local clubs, organizations, or online communities that align with your interests. Being part of a group can provide a sense of belonging and opportunities to make new friends.\n\n4. **Volunteer**: Helping others can be a fulfilling way to meet people and make a positive impact in your community. Volunteering often brings together individuals who care about similar causes.\n\n5. **Take Care of Your Well-Being**: Prioritize activities that support your mental and physical health, such as regular exercise, a balanced diet, adequate sleep, and mindfulness practices. Feeling good about yourself can make it easier to connect with others.\n\n6. **Seek Professional Support**: If feelings of loneliness persist or become overwhelming, talking to a mental health professional can provide support and strategies to cope.\n\n7. **Be Patient and Kind to Yourself**: Building friendships takes time, and it's normal to feel discouraged at times. Celebrate small steps and progress along the way.\n\nRemember, you're not alone, and there are many avenues to find connections and support. Reaching out, even when it's difficult, can lead to meaningful relationships over time.",
